man; bank president","primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nathaniel_Terry","primary_url_label":"Wikipedia"},"burial":{"plot_notes":"d. New Haven CT. Burial location unverified — possibly Grove Street Cemetery New Haven."},"cross_connections":[],"education":[{"institution_id":"INST022","school_name":"Yale College","type":"university","degree":"B.A.","graduation_year":1786,"notable":false,"institution_blurb":"Yale B.A. 1786. Mayor of Hartford 1824-1831."}],"bio":{"display_name":"Nathaniel Terry","first_name":"Nathaniel","last_name":"Terry","married_names":[],"photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1777483945/Nathaniel_Terry__Hartford_Fire_Insurance_Company_e6e2au.jpg"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST022","relationship":"alumnus","years":"1786"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"politics","header":"Mayor of Hartford for seven turbulent years","body":"He served as the 4th Mayor of Hartford from 1824 to 1831, spanning the city's transition from Federalist to Whig politics. He had previously served one term in the US House of Representatives (1817-1819) as a Federalist, and was a delegate to the 1818 Connecticut Constitutional Convention."},{"number":2,"category":"career","header":"President of Hartford Fire Insurance for 25 years","body":"He served as president of the Hartford Fire Insurance Company from 1810 to 1835 — a 25-year tenure spanning the company's early growth into one of New England's leading insurers. He simultaneously served as president of the Hartford Bank from 1819 to 1828."}],"former_ids":[],"career":[],"is_placeholder":false,"slug":"nathaniel-terry-1768"},"HD1331":{"id":"HD1331","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":6,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":true,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":true,"is_easter_egg":false,"generation_from_john_talcott":5,"hooker_talcott_convergence":true},"parents":{"father_id":"T00387","mother_id":"H00362"},"tags":["hooker_talcott_descent"],"sources":[{"entry":"863","label":"Edward Hooker 1909"}],"birth":{"year":1774,"month":1,"day":17,"city":"Hartford","state":"Connecticut"},"death":{"year":1841,"month":10,"day":26,"city":"Hartford","state":"Connecticut"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X00421","children_ids":["HD1345","HD1346","HD1347","HD1348","HD1349","HD1350","HD1351","HD1352"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1798,"date_month":3,"date_day":14,"location_city":"Hartford","location_state":"Connecticut"}],"gender":"female","artworks":["ART006"],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"narrative_blocks":[{"header":"Mother of an author and a Union general","body":"Catherine Wadsworth married Nathaniel Terry, one of Hartford's most prominent citizens, in 1798. The Hooker-Talcott blood that ran through her passed to her grandchildren: Rose Terry Cooke became one of New England's most celebrated regional authors, and Gen. Alfred Howe Terry led the Union assault on Fort Wagner and later commanded the Department of the Dakotas — present at the aftermath of the Little Bighorn. Catherine never lived to see either of them distinguish themselves; she died in 1841.","number":1,"category":"family"}],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM056"},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Catherine Wadsworth Terry","first_name":"Catherine","last_name":"Terry","maiden_name":"Wadsworth","married_names":["Terry"],"photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1777484083/catherineterry_gl7mvk.jpg"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"former_ids":[],"education":[],"career":[],"is_placeholder":false,"slug":"catherine-terry-1774"},"T00387":{"id":"T00387","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_john_talcott":4,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":true,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":true,"is_easter_egg":false},"tags":["slaveholder","politician","revolutionary_war","congressman","yale_connection","hooker_talcott_convergence"],"sources":[],"birth":{"year":1743,"month":7,"day":12,"city":"Hartford","state":"Connecticut"},"death":{"year":1804,"month":4,"day":30,"city":"Hartford","state":"Connecticut"},"political_offices":[{"title":"US Representative","jurisdiction":"Connecticut","dates":"1789-1795"},{"title":"Delegate","jurisdiction":"Continental Congress, Connecticut","dates":"multiple"},{"title":"Member","jurisdiction":"Connecticut State Legislature","dates":"multiple"}],"parents":{"father_id":"X00418","mother_id":"T00068"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"H00362","children_ids":["HD1329","HD1330","HD1331","HD1421","HD1422","HD1423","HD1424","HD1425","HD1426"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1754,"date_month":11,"date_day":19}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"civic_peer","related_id":"H00386","display_label":"Edwards won his seat — then handed it back","link_text":"Pierpont Edwards"},{"type":"parallel_descent","related_id":"H00348","display_label":"Talcott cousins who both supplied Washington's army from CT","link_text":"James Hooker"},{"type":"parallel_descent","related_id":"H00030","display_label":"EH notes their Standley cousinship — before he married a Hooker","link_text":"Hon. John Hooker"},{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"T00070","display_label":"Raised him from age four after his father died","link_text":"Col. Matthew Talcott"},{"type":"parallel_descent","related_id":"X00453","display_label":"His grandmother Elizabeth Standley was sister to Abigail Standley Hooker.","link_text":"Elizabeth Standley"}],"gender":"male","number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["politics","military","business"],"notable_blurb":"Commissary General; Rochambeau's host; 2nd President Bank NY","primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeremiah_Wadsworth","primary_url_label":"Wikipedia"},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"career","header":"Commissary General to both Washington and Rochambeau","body":"He served as Commissary General of the Continental Army from April 1778, then assumed the same role for Rochambeau's entire French force when it arrived in July 1780. By 1781 he had marshaled 855 horses, 600 oxen, 239 wagon conductors, and bread ovens along the route from Newport to the Hudson — making the Yorktown campaign possible."},{"number":2,"category":"legacy","header":"Washington and Rochambeau strategized in his Hartford parlor","body":"On September 20-22, 1780, Washington and Rochambeau held their war strategy conference at his Hartford home, joined by Hamilton, Knox, and Lafayette. The conference ended abruptly when news of Benedict Arnold's treason at West Point reached them."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Raised by the uncle who became his brother-in-law","body":"His uncle Matthew Talcott raised him from age four after his father died — and shipped him before the mast to improve his health. Years later he married Mehitable Russell, sister of Matthew Talcott's wife Mary, making his guardian also his brother-in-law."},{"number":4,"category":"career","header":"Second president of the Bank of New York","body":"He served as second President of the Bank of New York 1785-1786, working closely with his friend Alexander Hamilton on the early Republic's financial architecture. Edward Hooker called him 'one of the few men to whom the Revolutionary War proved a source of wealth.'"},{"number":5,"category":"legacy","header":"Father of the man who founded Wadsworth Atheneum","body":"His son Daniel Wadsworth founded the Wadsworth Atheneum in Hartford — the oldest continuously operating public art museum in America. The museum opened in 1844, four decades after Jeremiah's death."},{"number":6,"category":"politics","header":"Edwards beat him then handed back the seat","body":"In 1790 Pierpont Edwards — fellow Hartford figure and Hooker descendant — defeated him for the Connecticut Congressional seat. Edwards then declined to take it, forcing a special election that returned Wadsworth to Congress."},{"number":7,"category":"legacy","header":"WWII Liberty ship named in his honor","body":"During World War II the United States Liberty ship SS Jeremiah Wadsworth was named in his honor. It was a fitting echo of his Revolutionary commissary work — Liberty ships served as workhorses of America's wartime supply effort, just as he had supplied Washington and Rochambeau."}],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST052","relationship":"subject of founding portrait","institution_blurb":"His 1784 portrait by John Trumbull (ART030) hangs in the Atheneum his son Daniel founded."},{"institution_id":"INST0045","relationship":"member_not_listed","institution_blurb":"Part of Hartford's elite network that financed the Connecticut Land Company."},{"institution_id":"INST022","relationship":"alumnus"},{"institution_id":"INST035"}],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM003"},"education":[{"institution_id":"INST022","school_name":"Yale College","type":"honorary","degree":"Honorary degree","graduation_year":1796,"institution_blurb":"Honorary degrees from Yale and Dartmouth, 1796."}],"bio":{"display_name":"Col. Jeremiah Wadsworth","first_name":"Jeremiah","last_name":"Wadsworth","title":"Colonel","married_names":[],"photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1777483337/Jeremiah_Wadsworth_and_His_Son_Daniel_John_Trumbull_1784_ujnx74.jpg"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"former_ids":[],"career":[],"is_placeholder":false,"slug":"jeremiah-wadsworth-1743"},"H00362":{"id":"H00362","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":5,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1735,"city":"Middletown","state":"Connecticut"},"parents":{"father_id":"I00144","mother_id":"H00118"},"tags":["hooker_talcott_convergence"],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry 362"}],"death":{"year":1817,"month":3,"day":29,"city":"Hartford","state":"Connecticut"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"T00387","children_ids":["HD1329","HD1330","HD1331","HD1421","HD1422","HD1423","HD1424","HD1425","HD1426"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1754,"date_month":11,"date_day":19}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"historical_connection","related_id":"T00070","display_label":"He raised her future husband — and was already married to her sister","link_text":"Col. Matthew Talcott"}],"gender":"female","number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"narrative_blocks":[{"header":"Her marriage united Hartford's two founding bloodlines","body":"Mehitable Russell descended from Thomas Hooker through her mother Mary Pierpont Russell, granddaughter of Rev. James Pierpont and Mary Hooker. When she married Col. Jeremiah Wadsworth in 1767 — himself a Talcott descendant through his mother Abigail Talcott — their children became the convergence of the two men who had founded Hartford together in 1636: Thomas Hooker and John Talcott.","number":1},{"header":"The man who raised her husband had married","body":"Mehitable's sister Mary Russell had married Matthew Talcott of Middletown in 1740. When Rev. Daniel Wadsworth died in 1747 — leaving four-year-old Jeremiah fatherless — Matthew took the boy in and raised him. So when Mehitable married Jeremiah in 1764, she married into a household she already knew: the home of her own brother-in-law.","number":2},{"header":"Outlived her husband by thirteen years","body":"Jeremiah Wadsworth died on April 30, 1804, at age 60. Mehitable lived until March 29, 1817 — another thirteen years, to age 82. She outlived her daughter Harriet, who had died in Bermuda at 23.","number":3},{"number":4,"category":"family","header":"Cousins twice over before the wedding","body":"Her husband descended from Elizabeth Standley, whose sister Abigail had married John Hooker of Farmington. The Standley sisters meant the Wadsworth and Hooker lines were already kin — her marriage doubled a connection a century old."}],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST052","relationship":"mother of founder","institution_blurb":"Mother of Daniel Wadsworth (HD1330), who founded the Wadsworth Atheneum."}],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM003"},"bio":{"display_name":"Mehitable Russell","first_name":"Mehitable","last_name":"Russell","maiden_name":"Russell","married_names":["Wadsworth"],"photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1779233383/mehitablerussell_tnhzn0.png","bio_blurb":"Wife of the Revolution’s Commissary General"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"mehitable-russell-1735"}},"burialCemetery":null,"institutionsById":{"INST022":{"id":"INST022","primary_name":"American Board of Commissioners for Foreign Missions","name":"American Board of Commissioners for Foreign Missions","alt_names":["ABCFM","American Board"],"type":"missionary_society","founding_year":1810,"location":{"city":"Boston","state":"Massachusetts"},"primary_persons":["X00724"],"hooker_connected_people":["X00724","X02121","X02122","T01213","H00527","I01195"],"person_ids":[],"related_institutions":[],"related_landmarks":[],"tags":["native_american_contact","missionary"],"sources":[{"short":"Wikipedia","note":"Elias Cornelius (clergyman); ABCFM"}],"notes":"First American foreign-mission organization. Tree connections: Rev. Elias Cornelius (agent 1816, secretary 1831-32); Ainsworth and Harriet Ellsworth Blunt, missionaries to the Cherokee at Brainerd, Tennessee; Eliza Talcott, missionary to Japan; Rev. William Banfield Capron, Madura mission; Judge John Hooker, member."}},"crossConnections":[]}